Preprocessing and Early Models¶

A study of Asian Religious and Biblical Texts Data Set¶

Adrianna Grudzie, Mateusz Stczek

Data: archive.ics.uci.edu

Related article: www.researchgate.net

Introduction¶

In this task, there are 8 religious texts, 4 from Asia, 4 Biblical:

  • Upanishads,
  • Yoga Sutras,
  • Buddha Sutras,
  • Tao Te Ching,
  • Book of Wisdom,
  • Book of Proverbs,
  • Book of Ecclesiastes,
  • Book of Ecclesiasticus.

Each text has been divided into chapters (590 chapters in total) and the goal is to divide these chapters into clusters matching book of origin. This notebook contains various preprocessing steps as well as a few basic models.

Preprocessing¶

Next, we prepare a data frame df_chapters containing all useful information from the EDA, that is:

  • chapter length,
  • number of sentences,
  • average sentence length,
  • number of words (without stopwords),
  • number of unique words (without stopwords),
  • average word length,
  • chapter complexity (flesch reading ease),
  • positive/negative/neutral tinting of chapter,
  • bag of words instead of texts.
In [ ]:
df_chapters = pd.DataFrame(chapters, columns=['raw_chapter'])

df_chapters["chapter_length"] = [len(x) for x in chapters]
df_chapters["num_of_sentences"] = [len(sent_tokenize(x)) for x in chapters]
df_chapters["avg_sentence_len"] = [np.average([len(y) for y in sent_tokenize(x)]) for x in chapters]

# removing punctuation
tokenizer = nltk.RegexpTokenizer(r"\w+")
for i in range(len(chapters_without_stopwords)):
    text_tokens = tokenizer.tokenize(chapters_without_stopwords[i])
    chapters_without_stopwords[i] = " ".join(text_tokens)

df_chapters['num_of_words'] = [len(x.split()) for x in chapters]
df_chapters['num_of_words_wo_stopwords'] = [len(x.split()) for x in chapters_without_stopwords]
df_chapters['num_of_uniq_words'] = [len(set(x.split())) for x in chapters]
df_chapters['num_of_uniq_words_wo_stopwords'] = [len(set(x.split())) for x in chapters_without_stopwords]

import re
def num_of_letters(text):
    return len(re.findall('[a-zA-Z]',text))
df_chapters['num_of_letters'] = [num_of_letters(x) for x in chapters]

df_chapters['avg_word_length'] = df_chapters['num_of_letters'] / df_chapters['num_of_words']

from textstat import flesch_reading_ease
df_chapters["text_complex_fre"] = df_chapters.raw_chapter.apply(lambda x : flesch_reading_ease(x))

from textblob import TextBlob
df_chapters['polarity'] = [TextBlob(x).sentiment.polarity for x in chapters]
df_chapters['subjectivity'] = [TextBlob(x).sentiment.subjectivity for x in chapters]

K-Means elbow method with and without PCA¶

whiten=True is set, explanation here.

In this section there are 3 parts. Each is about KMeans trained on a different dataframe, PCA and the best number of clusters. Dataframes are used in the following order:

  • only statistical information about texts
  • both statistical information and a small bag of words
  • no statistical information and a big bag of words (the one provided)

Before we begin, here are a few useful functions. PCA is set to preserve at least 93% percent of variance.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import numpy as np

def pca_plot(df, title=''):
    pca = PCA(whiten=True).fit(df)
    plt.figure(figsize=(9,6))
    plt.plot(range(1, len(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)+1), np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_))
    plt.xlabel('number of components')
    plt.ylabel('cumulative explained variance')
    plt.title(title);

def make_plot(scores, x=None, title=''):
    x = x or list(range(1,len(scores) + 1))
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    plt.plot(x, scores)
    plt.xlabel('number of clusters')
    plt.ylabel('score (lower means clusters are tighter)')
    plt.ylim(0, plt.ylim()[1]*1.05)
    plt.title(title);

def elbow_method(df,title="Elbow method scores", k_max=None):
    k_max = k_max or 10
    scores = []
    for k in range(1, k_max+1):
        kmeans = KMeans(random_state=0, n_clusters=k).fit(df)
        scores.append(kmeans.score(df) * -1)
    make_plot(scores, x=list(range(1,k_max + 1)), title=title)

def elbow_method_PCA_93percent(df,title="Elbow method scores with PCA", k_max=None):
    elbow_method(PCA(whiten=True, n_components=0.93).fit_transform(df),title=title, k_max=k_max)

Some sources suggest the sufficient number of components for PCA as such that 90-95% of variance is preserved. (source)

To find the minimal number of components preserving 0.9 of overall data variance, we can easily use the n_components parameter in PCA from sklearn package and set it to 0.9. The result is presented below (here again, the dataset used contains statistical info about chapters only, no BoW).

KMeans¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

# funkcja z materiaw z zaj
def plot_kmeans_clusters(X, n_clusters):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, random_state=0)
    kmeans.fit(X)
    y_kmeans = kmeans.predict(X)
    plt.figure(figsize = (6, 4))

    plt.scatter(X.iloc[:, 0], X.iloc[:, 1], c=y_kmeans, s=30, cmap='viridis')

    centers = kmeans.cluster_centers_
    plt.scatter(centers[:, 0], centers[:, 1], c='black', s=200, alpha=0.75)
    plt.title('K-means clusters n_clusters = ' + str(n_clusters))
    plt.show()

Summary¶

Texts are too similar to divide chapters into 8 books they originate from. However dividing into 4 religions seems like a reasonable goal. As for now, even TSNE did not separate 4 religions, only made some differences between Christian texts and others.

This time we checked PCA and scaling. For the next time we plan to check different scalers (to deal with outliers breaking K-Means) as well as different algorithms such as Agglomeratuce Clustering and others.
